{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":226841,"duration_api_ms":226809,"ttft_ms":157907,"ttft_stream_ms":5083,"time_to_request_ms":28,"num_turns":2,"result":"I've completed the structured code review. The JSON response covers all required fields (summary, findings, tested, not_tested, residual_risks) with 10 findings across the requested scope dimensions (correctness, security, regression, test_gaps, maintainability).\n\nKey takeaways from my review:\n\n**Most significant concerns (medium):**\n1. **Permission mode weakening** — changing `--permission-mode` from `plan` to `default` removes a CLI-layer read-only enforcement, leaving only `--tools \"\"` and the system prompt as guards. This is the most security-relevant change.\n2. **Untested `main()` entrypoint** — all CLI tests bypass argparse; routing, exit codes, and `--actor` handling have zero coverage.\n3. **Claude CLI flag dependency** — `--system-prompt`/`--json-schema` compatibility is only verified by mocked tests plus one manual smoke, leaving version drift uncaught.\n\n**Lower-severity but worth fixing:**\n- Non-atomic state writes (corruption risk on interrupt)\n- Dead constants (`STATE_SCHEMA`, `NON_TERMINAL_STATES`)\n- Weak evidence-path validation (existence ≠ confinement)\n- `_extract_review_content` doesn't type-check `structured_output`\n- TOCTOU window between validate and write\n\n**Positive observations:**\n- Static contract tests are a strong drift-detection guard\n- BOM tolerance is consistently tested on both read paths\n- The `test_run_uses_resolved_claude_executable` test is thorough about the new command shape\n- Codex-only actor gating on `advance_run` is properly enforced and tested\n- The validate-before-commit-candidate pattern (with the `utc_now` mock test) confirms failed validation doesn't corrupt state","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"bb84eea7-24bb-4f3b-8d7b-1fc37e9e7d76","total_cost_usd":0.381817,"usage":{"input_tokens":20432,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":9664,"output_tokens":10993,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"glm-5.2[1m]":{"inputTokens":20432,"outputTokens":10993,"cacheReadInputTokens":9664,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.381817,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"The changeset adds a minimal Harness CLI (validate/advance), static contract drift tests, and hardens the Claude review adapter (resolved executable, stdin prompt, BOM tolerance, structured_output preference, JSON-schema-constrained output). Test coverage for happy paths and the new adapter command shape is solid, and the static-contract tests are a meaningful regression guard. However, the adapter weakens its defense-in-depth posture by switching `--permission-mode` from `plan` to `default`, the CLI's `main()`/argparse layer is untested, state writes are non-atomic, and the new adapter depends on Claude CLI flags (`--system-prompt`, `--json-schema`) whose version compatibility is only verified by a manual smoke. Issues below are scoped to correctness, security, regression, test gaps, and maintainability.","findings":[{"severity":"medium","title":"Permission mode weakened from 'plan' to 'default' reduces read-only defense-in-depth","evidence":"In the constructed `command` list, `--permission-mode` was changed from `\"plan\"` to `\"default\"` while relying solely on `--tools \"\"` and the `REVIEW_SYSTEM_PROMPT` (which only *instructs* read-only behavior) to prevent side effects. `plan` mode enforces read-only at the CLI layer; `default` does not, so any future regression that re-enables tools would silently grant write capability. The test `test_run_uses_resolved_claude_executable` only asserts the value is `default`, locking in the weaker posture.","recommendation":"Either revert to `--permission-mode plan` (preferred for a read-only reviewer) or document explicitly why default mode is required and add a guard test asserting the tool list stays empty. Do not rely on the system prompt as the sole read-only enforcement.","file":"mcp/claude-review/adapter.py","line":327},{"severity":"medium","title":"CLI main()/argparse entrypoint has no unit coverage","evidence":"`tests/test_harness_cli.py` exercises `cli.validate_run` and `cli.advance_run` directly but never calls `cli.main([...])`. As a result, the subparser wiring (`required=True`), exit-code paths (0/1/2), `--actor` default handling, the `HarnessCliError` -> return 1 mapping, and `parser.error('unknown command')` are all untested. A regression in `main()` (e.g., dropping the actor check or mis-routing commands) would not be caught.","recommendation":"Add tests that invoke `cli.main(['validate', <run_dir>])`, `cli.main(['advance', <run_dir>, <status>, '--actor', 'claude-code'])` (expect non-zero), and an unknown-command case to lock in exit codes and routing.","file":"tests/test_harness_cli.py","line":1},{"severity":"medium","title":"Adapter depends on Claude CLI flags (--system-prompt, --json-schema) without version/feature detection","evidence":"The new command hard-codes `--system-prompt`, `--json-schema`, and `--permission-mode default`. Tests mock `subprocess.run`, so they cannot detect whether the installed Claude CLI actually supports these flags or the `structured_output` field. Verification notes only one manual smoke run; older/newer CLI builds may reject unknown flags or omit `structured_output`, causing `_extract_review_content` to fall through to `result`/`content`.","recommendation":"Pin and document the supported Claude CLI version, add a `--help`/feature probe in the wrapper, or add an integration-style test that asserts the real CLI accepts these flags. Monitor `structured_output` presence in production envelopes.","file":"mcp/claude-review/adapter.py","line":318},{"severity":"low","title":"advance_run writes state.json non-atomically (corruption risk on interruption)","evidence":"`path.write_text(json.dumps(candidate, indent=2) + \"\\n\", encoding=\"utf-8\")` overwrites `state.json` in place. An interrupt or crash mid-write leaves a truncated file, which would then fail `validate_run` on every subsequent invocation with no recovery path. There is also a TOCTOU window between `validate_run` reading the file and the re-read inside `advance_run`.","recommendation":"Write to a sibling temp file (e.g., `state.json.tmp`) in the same directory and `os.replace()` for atomic commit. Consider file locking if concurrent CLI use is possible.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":146},{"severity":"low","title":"Dead module constants: STATE_SCHEMA and NON_TERMINAL_STATES are unused","evidence":"`STATE_SCHEMA = ROOT / \"harness\" / \"schemas\" / \"state.schema.json\"` is defined but `validate_state` rebuilds the path from `root / \"harness\" / \"schemas\" / \"state.schema.json\"`. `NON_TERMINAL_STATES = set(NORMAL_TRANSITIONS)` is computed but never referenced. Both are misleading maintainability traps.","recommendation":"Either use `STATE_SCHEMA` (joined with `root`) inside `validate_state` and remove `NON_TERMINAL_STATES`, or delete both. Keeping dead constants invites future divergence.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":16},{"severity":"low","title":"Evidence path validation accepts any existing file regardless of location","evidence":"`validate_evidence_paths` checks only `candidate.exists()` for `root / evidence_path` or `run_dir / evidence_path`. A state.json could declare `/etc/passwd` or any repo file as evidence and pass validation. The check proves existence but not relevance or confinement, weakening the audit-trail guarantee the CLI advertises.","recommendation":"Confine evidence paths to within `run_dir` (resolve and compare parents), or explicitly document the trust assumption that state.json is authoritatively written only by codex. Reject absolute paths that escape the run directory.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":104},{"severity":"low","title":"_extract_review_content trusts structured_output without type validation","evidence":"The new branch `if \"structured_output\" in parsed: content = parsed[\"structured_output\"]` fires whenever the key exists, even if the value is `None`, a string, or a list. Downstream normalization assumes dict-shaped content; a malformed-but-present `structured_output` could yield a confusing schema error instead of falling back to `result`. No test covers this case.","recommendation":"Guard with `isinstance(parsed.get(\"structured_output\"), dict)` before preferring it, and add a test where `structured_output` is null/non-dict to confirm graceful fallback.","file":"mcp/claude-review/adapter.py","line":583},{"severity":"low","title":"TOCTOU window between validate_run and write in advance_run","evidence":"`advance_run` calls `validate_run` (which reads state.json), then immediately re-opens and re-reads state.json before writing. If another process advances the run between these calls, the validation result is stale and an invalid interleaving could be committed. Single-actor CLI use mostly masks this, but the pattern is unsafe by construction.","recommendation":"Read once, validate the in-memory copy, then atomically commit. If concurrency is in scope, add an advisory lock.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":127},{"severity":"info","title":"State machine has no exit transitions from exceptional states","evidence":"`NORMAL_TRANSITIONS` defines `external_review_unavailable -> risk_accepted` only (no return to `reviewing`), and the exception targets `blocked` / `needs_user_decision` have no outgoing edges. Once a run enters these states, the CLI cannot move it forward; recovery requires hand-editing state.json. This may be intentional but is undocumented.","recommendation":"Document the policy (e.g., 'exceptional states require human intervention outside the CLI') or add supervised recovery transitions with tests.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":12},{"severity":"info","title":"Encoding asymmetry: state.json read as utf-8-sig but written as utf-8","evidence":"`load_json` reads with `encoding=\"utf-8-sig\"` (strips BOM), while `advance_run` writes with `encoding=\"utf-8\"` (no BOM). Round-tripping therefore silently drops a BOM. The `test_validate_accepts_bom_prefixed_state_json` test confirms BOM-tolerant reads but no test asserts write-side behavior, so the asymmetry is implicit.","recommendation":"Confirm the BOM-stripping is intended (it appears to be, given Windows tooling), and add a brief code comment or test documenting that BOMs are accepted on input and normalized away on output.","file":"harness/cli.py","line":60}],"tested":["BOM-tolerant payload loading via utf-8-sig (test_wrapper_load_payload_accepts_utf8_bom)","Adapter prefers structured_output over result/content (test_normalize_prefers_structured_output)","Resolved claude executable used as command[0] (test_run_uses_resolved_claude_executable)","Prompt passed via stdin input= rather than positional arg","New flags --system-prompt and --json-schema present in command","Permission mode value pinned to 'default'","Encoding params utf-8 / errors=replace asserted","CLI validate accepts example-fast-doc-change","CLI validate rejects missing evidence path","CLI validate accepts BOM-prefixed state.json","CLI advance permits codex normal transition and bumps updated_at","CLI advance does not persist candidate when validation fails","CLI advance rejects invalid transition from completed","CLI advance rejects non-codex actor","Static contract: lifecycle workflow registry matches state schema enums and track constraints","Static contract: state-authority normal+exceptional states match schema status enum","Static contract: review status mapping matches adapter.TERMINAL_STATUSES","review_content_json_schema required keys and additionalProperties=False shape"],"not_tested":["CLI main() / argparse routing, exit codes (0/1/2), and --actor default handling","Real Claude CLI invocation with --system-prompt / --json-schema / --permission-mode default (subprocess.run is mocked in all adapter tests)","_extract_review_content behavior when structured_output is None or non-dict","Recovery transitions out of blocked / needs_user_decision / external_review_unavailable","Atomicity / crash-safety of state.json writes in advance_run","Concurrent advance_run invocations (TOCTOU window)","Evidence path confinement to run_dir / repo root (only existence is checked)","validate_run behavior with permission-denied or unreadable state.json","Compatibility of new adapter flags across Claude CLI versions","Schema rejection of malformed severity / findings emitted by a real Claude run","Effect of --tools \"\" across Claude CLI versions"],"residual_risks":["Claude CLI version drift: --system-prompt, --json-schema, structured_output, and the meaning of --permission-mode default may change between releases; only one manual smoke confirmed current behavior.","Real Claude output variability: schema-constrained parsing still depends on the model honoring --json-schema; malformed-but-present structured_output could produce confusing errors.","Permission posture relies on --tools \"\" plus a system prompt; the removal of plan mode reduces defense-in-depth if tools are ever re-enabled.","advance_run is not atomic and not locked; a crash or concurrent invocation could corrupt or stale-write state.json.","Evidence path validation proves file existence only, not that the file is the intended artifact for the run.","The local `pip install -r mcp/claude-review/requirements.txt` performed during verification mutated the active Python environment without adding a root lockfile, so CI/reproducibility is not guaranteed.","Exceptional states (blocked, needs_user_decision, external_review_unavailable) have no CLI recovery path; manual state.json edits remain necessary."]},"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"7bd00184-cd50-4a0d-a142-8ba78ba62217"}

